    <prj:ScienceGoal mode="Standard">
        <prj:name>C18O2-1</prj:name>
        <prj:note>Our primary goal is to determine the gas temperature structure deep inside the disk of HL Tau and thus provide a direct, observational determination of the mid-plane snowline radii. We choose the C18O 2-1(219.56 GHz)/ 6-5(658.54 GHz) lines as our primary targets. In band 6, the H2S/H2_34S 2(2,0)-2(1,1) lines can be obtained simultaneously with the C18O 2-1 transition; while in band 9 the C17O 6-5, C18O6-5, and H2S 4(2,2)-4(1,3) lines can be observed in one spectral setting. The expected line widths are 6 km/s based on Keplerian motion in the moderately inclined  HL Tau disk (i=47 deg). We choose a spectral resolution of ~0.1 km/s to retain a high fidelity sampling of the disk kinetics, and note that we can bin to lower resolution if needed to increase the signal-to-noise ratio. 

We aim to image HL Tau at 220GHz with a spatial resolution of 0.2" (28 AU at 140pc), which is chosen to match the expected snow line location for NH3 and H2S hydrates. The primary C18O targets directly measure the temperature profile, and the H2S 216GHz emission thus provides an excellent secondary means of distinguishing the warm disk case from the cold one, since the line emission will be spatially resolved in a warm disk  but unresolved in a cold disk, and will provide a direct chemical test of the snow line scenario. For band 9, we propose a larger spatial resolution of 0.4" due to the low atmospheric transmission in this window. The schedule of the corresponding array configurations also makes observations of HL Tau possible during night time. </prj:note>
