        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected line widths are 6 km/s based on Keplerian motion in the moderately inclined HL Tau disk (i=47 deg). We choose a spectral resolution of ~0.1km/s to retain a high fidelity sampling of the disk kinetics for C18O2-1 line to confirm its disk origin. For the H2S 220-211 line, we will bin the channels for higher sensitivity and note that we can bin to lower resolution if needed to increase the signal-to-noise ratio. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to image HL Tau C18O 2-1 and H2S 220-221 emissions at 220GHz with a spatial resolution of 0.2" (28AU at 140pc), which is chosen to resolve the second dark ring (32 AU) and to resolve the expected snowline location of NH3 at H2S hydrates in the warm disk case. 

The HL Tau continuum images from ALMA scientific verfication campaign show that the radius of the dust disk is ~1". All of our interested snowlines are expected to be within this radius. Thus we acquire the largest angular scale to be ~2.5".  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected line fluxes are listed in Table 1, for both the warm and cold disk cases. The moment zero maps of simulationed line emissions are shown in Figure 2. 

To ensure our line detection, all of the sensitivity calculations are based on the line fluxes in the cold disk case. We aim to obtain at least 3 sigma detections for C18O 2-1 emission at each (0.1km/s) spectral channel within 3.8 km/s (the Keplerian velocity at the radius of the second dark ring) offset from the rest frequency of lines, in order to be sensitive to gas emission from the inner 32 AU region. Our simulation of C18O 2-1 emission shows that at the line wing velocity channels, the expected peak intensity is ~12 mJy/beam, we thus require a sensitity of 4mJy/beam at 0.1km/s wide channel. For H2S 220-211 emission, we expect to have a signal-to-noise ratio of 4 at its moment zero map (Figure 2(h)).  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
