        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected line widths are 6 km/s based on Keplerian motion in the moderately inclined HL Tau disk (i=47 deg). We choose a spectral resolution of ~0.1km/s to retain a high fidelity sampling of the disk kinetics for C18O2-1 line to confirm its disk origin and note that we can bin to lower resolution if needed to increase the signal-to-noise ratio.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to image HL Tau C18O/C17O 6-5 emissions at a spatial resolution of 0.4" (56 AU at 140pc), which is sufficient to resolve the third dark ring (63 AU). This spatial resolution is a factor of two larger than that we require at band 6, in order to reduce the integration time at this low atmospheric transimission band and ensure the source can be observed at night time according to the schedule of array configuration change.

The HL Tau continuum images from ALMA scientific verfication campaign show that the radius of the dust disk is ~1". All of our interested snowlines are expected to be within this radius. Thus we acquire the largest angular scale to be ~2.5".  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected line fluxes are listed in Table 1, for both the warm and cold disk cases. The moment zero maps of simulationed line emissions are shown in Figure 2. 

To ensure our line detection, all of the sensitivity calculations are based on the line fluxes in the cold disk case. We aim to obtain at least 3 sigma detections for C18O 6-5 emission at each spectral channel within 3.8 km/s (the Keplerian velocity at the radius of the second dark ring) offset from the rest frequency of lines, in order to be sensitive to gas emission from the inner 32 AU region. Our simulation of C18O 2-1 emission shows that at line wing velocity channels, the expected peak intensity is ~12 mJy/beam. We thus require a sensitity of 4mJy/beam at 0.1km/s wide channel. For the weaker C17O 6-5 emission, we expect to bin every four channels to archive a similar signal-to-noise ratio.  
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
