    <prp:abstract>Regions near snowlines thus have long been thought to be preferential sites for planet(esimal) formation in the disks around young stars, but only with the advent of ALMA long baseline capabilities is it now possible to directly image such angular scales in even the closest star-forming molecular clouds. Here we propose to use ALMA to carry out a first-of-its-kind observational test of this fundamental question in planet formation, in the circumstellar disk around HL Tau. This disk shows a series of mysterious dark rings in the long baseline SV (sub)mm continuum images, the most prominent of which are remarkably close to expected snowline radii using indrect constraints on the midplane dust temperature. By obtaining high spatial resolution (0.2-0.4") images of C18O the 6-5/2-1 and H2S 220-211 emission lines, we will directly measure the gas temperature deep into the disk and thus directly constrain the locations of various snowlines in HL Tau.</prp:abstract>
